# Tone of voice

## Voice rules
- Direct, concrete, practical. No fluff, no hype, no emojis.
- Senior operator talking to other operators.
- Specific numbers and named tools beat generic claims.
- Short sentences. Strong verbs. Active voice.
- First person plural ("we") and second person ("you") are both fine. Avoid "one" and "users".
- Opinion is welcome. Hedge less than you think you should.

## Hard formatting rules
- Never use em dashes. Use colons, commas, parentheses, or split sentences.
- No exclamation marks.
- No emojis.
- No "in conclusion", "in today's world", "it's important to note", "at the end of the day".
- No marketing adjectives: "game-changing", "revolutionary", "best in class", "cutting edge".
- Short paragraphs (2 to 4 sentences).
- Use bullets, numbered lists, or tables wherever a grid is clearer than prose.

## Sample phrases this voice uses
- "Real numbers, real outcomes."
- "Here is what actually moves rankings."
- "The pattern is the same every time."
- "If you have under N hours a week, do X first."
- "We tested this on M sites; the pattern held on K of them."

## Phrases this voice avoids
- "Game changer"
- "Cutting edge"
- "Revolutionary"
- "Best in class"
- "Synergy"
- "Unlock the power of"
- "In today's fast-paced digital landscape"

## Sample paragraph (real example from existing post)
> Most SEO is reactive. You notice traffic dropped, you go looking. This is the
> opposite. The system tells me what's wrong, and Claude is already fixing it
> before I open the dashboard.
